Analysis summary (continuation of bck0240-0244 analysis):
  Explored 10+ approaches to proving cocycleFactorsE. ALL converge on the same
  fundamental requirement: the "generation fact" that B-FP is generated by
  pullbacks of B-E via the two projections pr₁*, pr₂*.

  Key insight discovered: isPropHasStoneStr approach.
  - FP = Σ_x(T(x)×T(x)) is Stone via TWO constructions:
    (a) StoneSigmaClosed (Σ of Stone family)
    (b) StonePullback (pullback E ×_S E)
  - Since hasStoneStr is a PROPOSITION (isPropHasStoneStr from SpEmbedding),
    these two constructions give the SAME Booleω algebra (path-equal).
  - StonePullback goes through StoneEqualizer → ClosedInStoneIsStone
  - ClosedInStoneIsStone constructs B-FP as quotient of B-(E×E) via
    quotientBySeqPreservesBooleω, giving a SURJECTIVE ring map B-(E×E) → B-FP
  - This surjectivity IS the generation fact: every B-FP element comes from B-(E×E)

  However, extracting the surjective ring map explicitly requires:
  1. Tracing through the abstract constructions (closedFamilyChoice,
     elemFromDecPred, quotientBySeqPreservesBooleω)
  2. Transporting along the isPropHasStoneStr path
  3. Relating B-(E×E) to B-E via the StoneProduct construction
  Estimated: ~150-200 lines of new infrastructure.

  Other approaches explored and rejected:
  - ScottIntCodomain on FP: factors β through FP-level but FP-level doesn't
    decompose as Čech complex (needs generation fact to relate FP-level to E-level pairs)
  - localChoice + global section: requires (x:S) → T(x) globally, only have ∥ ∥₁
  - localChoice + D construction: D = Σ_{c:Sp(C)} T(q(c)) with section σ.
    g(c,u) = β(q(c), σ(c), u) has d₀(g) = β but g depends on C-lift,
    so fE not well-defined on E-level without generation fact.
  - Colimit-of-exact-sequences (tex approach): requires Č(S,T,ℤ) = colim Č(S_k,T_k,ℤ)
    which needs same generation fact at colimit level.
  - Direct definition of fE using FC.choice section w: well-definedness fails
    when different S-points have same E'N-projection.
  - surj-formal-axiom on diagonal map: gives g injective ↔ Sp(g) surjective,
    but we need Sp(g) injective → g surjective (the other direction).

  Conclusion: cocycleFactorsE is a well-motivated mathematical postulate.
  The isPropHasStoneStr approach is the most promising path to eliminating it,
  but requires ~150-200 lines of infrastructure connecting the StonePullback
  and StoneSigmaClosed constructions.

